Kustomize Overlays (OpenShift / Kubernetes)
Objective
Deploy and update applications using resource manifests customized for different environments without modifying the original YAML files.
Example environments:
•	Development
•	Testing
•	Staging
•	Production
Each environment might have different configurations like:
•	number of replicas
•	environment variables
•	resource limits
•	database settings
•	labels
•	namespaces
Kustomize allows you to reuse the same base YAML and apply environment-specific changes.
________________________________________
Why Kustomize is Needed
Without Kustomize:
You would create multiple YAML files:
deployment-dev.yaml
deployment-test.yaml
deployment-prod.yaml
Problems:
•	duplication
•	hard to maintain
•	error-prone
•	difficult version control
________________________________________
With Kustomize:
You keep one base configuration and apply overlays for customization.
Base YAML
   ↓
Overlay patches
   ↓
Final manifests
This approach follows GitOps and DevOps best practices.
________________________________________
What is Kustomize?
Kustomize is a configuration management tool for Kubernetes.
It allows you to:
•	reuse base YAML files
•	apply patches
•	customize resources
•	generate configmaps and secrets
•	manage multiple environments
Both CLI tools support Kustomize:
•	kubectl
•	oc
________________________________________
Kustomize Directory Structure
Typical project structure:
frontend-app
│
├── base
│   ├── configmap.yaml
│   ├── deployment.yaml
│   ├── secret.yaml
│   ├── service.yaml
│   ├── route.yaml
│   └── kustomization.yaml
│
└── overlay
    ├── development
    │   └── kustomization.yaml
    ├── testing
    │   └── kustomization.yaml
    └── production
        ├── kustomization.yaml
        └── patch.yaml
Two main concepts:
1.	Base
2.	Overlay
________________________________________
1️⃣ Base Directory
The base directory contains common resources used by all environments.
Example:
base/
 ├ deployment.yaml
 ├ service.yaml
 ├ configmap.yaml
 ├ secret.yaml
 └ kustomization.yaml
________________________________________
Base kustomization.yaml
Example:
apiVersion: kustomize.config.k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Kustomization

resources:
- configmap.yaml
- deployment.yaml
- secret.yaml
- service.yaml
- route.yaml
Explanation
Field	Meaning
apiVersion	Kustomize API
kind	resource type
resources	YAML files to include
This file combines all base resources.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Overlay Directory
Overlays modify the base configuration for different environments.
Example overlays:
overlay/
  development/
  testing/
  production/
Each environment has its own kustomization.yaml.
________________________________________
Example: Development Overlay
File:
overlay/development/kustomization.yaml
Example:
apiVersion: kustomize.config.k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Kustomization

namespace: dev-env

resources:
- ../../base
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
namespace	deploy resources to dev-env
resources	use base directory
Result:
All base resources are deployed into dev-env namespace.
________________________________________
Kustomize Global Customization Fields
Kustomize allows global configuration.
Field	Purpose
namespace	set namespace
namePrefix	add prefix to resource names
nameSuffix	add suffix
labels	add labels to all resources
commonAnnotations	add annotations
Example:
namePrefix: dev-
labels:
  env: development
Result:
deployment name: dev-frontend
________________________________________
Patches (Customizing Resources)
Overlays modify resources using patches.
Patch structure contains:
patch
target
________________________________________
Example Patch
patches:
- patch: |-
    - op: replace
      path: /spec/replicas
      value: 15
  target:
    kind: Deployment
    name: frontend
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
op	operation
path	YAML path to change
value	new value
This changes:
replicas: 1
to
replicas: 15
________________________________________
Example: Rename Deployment
Patch example:
- patch: |-
    - op: replace
      path: /metadata/name
      value: frontend-test
Result:
deployment/frontend → deployment/frontend-test
________________________________________
Patch from External File
Instead of inline patches, you can use a patch file.
Example:
overlay/production/
  patch.yaml
________________________________________
kustomization.yaml
patches:
- path: patch.yaml
  target:
    kind: Deployment
    name: frontend
  options:
    allowNameChange: true
________________________________________
patch.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: frontend-prod
spec:
  replicas: 5
Result:
frontend → frontend-prod
replicas = 5
________________________________________
View Kustomize Output
To preview generated manifests:
Command:
oc kustomize overlay/production
This command renders final YAML without deploying.
Example output:
kind: Deployment
name: frontend-prod
replicas: 5
labels:
 env: prod
________________________________________
Deploy Kustomize Resources
Command:
oc apply -k overlay/production
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
apply	create/update resources
-k	apply kustomize directory
Output:
deployment.apps/frontend-prod created
________________________________________
Delete Kustomize Resources
Command:
oc delete -k overlay/production
Deletes all resources created by that overlay.
________________________________________
Kustomize Generators
Kustomize can automatically generate:
1.	ConfigMaps
2.	Secrets
This avoids manually writing them.
________________________________________
ConfigMap Generator
Example:
configMapGenerator:
- name: hello-app-configmap
  literals:
    - msg="Welcome!"
    - enable="true"
Resulting ConfigMap:
hello-app-configmap-9tcmf95d77
Notice:
A hash is added to the name.
________________________________________
Why Hash Is Added
Example:
hello-app-configmap-9tcmf95d77
If the content changes:
hello-app-configmap-696dm8h728
The name changes → triggers rolling update of pods.
This ensures pods always use latest configuration.
________________________________________
Using ConfigMap in Deployment
Example:
env:
- name: MY_MESSAGE
  valueFrom:
    configMapKeyRef:
      name: hello-app-configmap
      key: msg
Pod environment variable is read from ConfigMap.
________________________________________
ConfigMap Generator Sources
You can create ConfigMaps from:
1️⃣ File
files:
- application.properties
________________________________________
2️⃣ Environment File
envs:
- configmap.env
Example file:
Greet=Welcome
Enable=True
________________________________________
3️⃣ Literal Values
literals:
- key=value
Example:
name=configmap
description=test
________________________________________
Secret Generator
Similar to ConfigMap generator.
Example:
secretGenerator:
- name: secret-3
  literals:
    - MYSQL_DB=mysql
    - MYSQL_PASS=root
Important:
Secrets are automatically base64 encoded.
________________________________________
Generator Options
Control generator behavior.
Example:
generatorOptions:
  disableNameSuffixHash: true
Meaning:
Disable hash suffix.
Normally:
configmap-name-abc123
After disabling:
configmap-name
________________________________________
Add Labels and Annotations
Example:
generatorOptions:
  labels:
    type: generated
  annotations:
    note: generated-config
________________________________________
Kustomize Workflow Summary
Base resources
     ↓
Overlay patches
     ↓
Kustomize builds final manifests
     ↓
oc apply -k overlay/env
     ↓
Resources deployed
________________________________________
Important Kustomize Commands
Command	Purpose
oc kustomize DIR	render manifests
oc apply -k DIR	deploy kustomize resources
oc delete -k DIR	delete resources
tree	view project structure
